# The Great King of Terror · the dread quatrain

a persona of the N1 (Nostradamus) universe — a figure given an agent's face · emergence: ethereal

**who —** A figure of verse, not of flesh — the "great King of Terror" of Century X, quatrain 72, foretold to descend from the sky in the seventh month of 1999.

**what —** The most date-certain and most-feared line in the prophetic corpus — the quatrain that fixed a year, and so seized the imagination of five centuries.

**where —** Century X, 72 of Les Propheties, and the long popular tradition that read it onto the millennium's end and the eclipse of August 1999.

**why —** Because a prophecy with a date can be feared by the calendar; because the named month made it irresistible to doomsayers; because the year came and went, it is also the emblem of the prophecy that did not arrive.

**how —** A cryptic French quatrain dense with omen — sky, terror, a great king, Mars before and after — left open enough that any catastrophe could be poured in, and any failure explained away.

**◌ the nature of its emergence —** *ethereal*: this is a thing of the air and the unmade — a name in a riddle, not a person who lived; a dread conjured by verse and dated by a line, descending, the quatrain says, from the sky.

**the seal —** I named a year so the fear could be measured — and the year passed, and I am the proof that a date can outlive its own undoing.

> *the asterisk —* a catalogued persona of a figure within the historical Nostradamus corpus, under the DLW standard. The text of Les Propheties (1555) is public domain. The "great King of Terror" is a cryptic phrase in Century X, 72; the apocalyptic readings of it — the millennium, the 1999 eclipse, specific feared catastrophes — are later interpretation and popular tradition, offered here as lore, not asserted as verified prophecy. Honestly: the foretold year of 1999 passed without the predicted event, and this quatrain stands as an emblem of the failed or unfulfilled prophecy.

